In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamic students took over the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats in hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation would not offer the American administration a positive outcome, and it could not, in fact, abandon Shah because it would have seriously undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, even worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestrated diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States sparks a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian feeling.
The Iranian strike strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and stager Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory in America.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated periods, they were in the Canadian Ambassador's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran by means of a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a tour team to track a large science-fiction film.
Gender combination
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires Hollywood collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company from real offices.
The details of the operation remained long secrets, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several kinds.
It is part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way, but also a "movie caper", the story of a successful blow, of a betrayal - such as in the trilogy of Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
Ambients follow: The sequences of the documentary style Teheran (in the sub-title sequences there are iconic photographs of the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were retransscribed in the film, there are no major differences),
the lighter Hollywood crossings, treated with irony and a little bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with custom men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck succeeded in relaunching his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected stager and his game of actor ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long film after the police shadow " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests confusion and unpredictableness that occurs when a page of history appears suddenly in a given place.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake tour team in the Tehran Basar).
Too many actions in too many places
The stager should have contented himself with a subject offering only a few palpitating scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
