Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain from the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request to obtain observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, since it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she no longer supports the American position.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, without however showing too much criticism of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain from the vote on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposes this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to say defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are therefore faced with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still working to find this role, but they are on the path of a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, such as in France or Britain
What exactly does the term "normal" for Germans mean?
It demonstrates the willingness to adopt independent positions of those of the United States and of European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected Germany's position towards the conflict in the Middle East and the absence of the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has important developments in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend the public opinion, but also the elite of the Arab countries.
This is without a doubt a decisive element.
However, I would not give too much importance to it, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is a decisive element in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany sleep in its relations with the United States by opting to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are different.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic policy scene.
I believe that the Obama administration has shown a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that real differences in opinion are not so great that they always appear to be.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiastically addressing Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes things easy for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will play a role as a locomotive in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been sensitive.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that marks their independence more.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or is it always difficult to take on the role of a plan?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable to it and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we note that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
This is not easy for the Germans.
In fact, this is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy only decreases, but at this point the EU does not fill this gap, so who is it?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's disgusting to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Washington Transatlantic Academy, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
